## 4. Analysis

### Time Complexity Comparison

| Algorithm   | Best Case  | Average Case | Worst Case |
| ----------- | ---------- | ------------ | ---------- |
| Bubble Sort | O(n)       | O(n²)        | O(n²)      |
| Quick Sort  | O(n log n) | O(n log n)   | O(n²)      |

### Why Quick Sort is Preferred

1. Quick Sort has an average time complexity of O(n log n), making it much faster than Bubble Sort for large datasets.
2. Bubble Sort requires multiple comparisons and swaps, resulting in O(n²) complexity.
3. Quick Sort uses the divide-and-conquer technique, which improves efficiency.
4. E-commerce platforms handle a large number of orders, so Quick Sort provides better performance and scalability.
5. Quick Sort is widely used in real-world applications because of its speed and efficient memory usage.

## Conclusion

Bubble Sort is simple to implement but inefficient for large datasets due to its O(n²) complexity. Quick Sort is generally preferred because it offers O(n log n) average-case performance, making it faster and more suitable for sorting customer orders in large-scale e-commerce platforms.

